10621nam a22012615i 9783110769609DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2023932805  a97831107696097 a10.1515/97831107696092doi  a(DE-B1597)611853  a(OCoLC)1382693666  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aP115.35b.T73 2023. 7aLAN0090502bisacsh00aTranslanguaging for Equal Opportunities :bSpeaking Romani at School /ced. by János Imre Heltai, Eszter Tarsoly. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (XX, 321 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aContributions to the Sociology of Language [CSL] ,x1861-0676 ;v12100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAuthor Information -- tList of videos -- tTranscription conventions -- tGlossing abbreviations -- tForeword -- t1 Introduction. Collaborative research writing: Multiplicity of realities, texts, and translanguaging -- tPart I: Romani and translanguaging: Theoretical considerations -- t2 Non-standardised ways of speaking and language-policy regimes -- t3 Romani and translanguaging -- t4 Perspectives on friction and collaboration in Tiszavasvári -- tPart II: Methodological approaches: Translanguaging and participatory ethnography -- t5 Data collection: Linguistic ethnographic research and participatory approaches -- t6 Data processing: Retaining multiple perspectives and voices through abduction, in analysis, and translation -- tPart III: Perspectives on translanguaging educational practices in the Tiszavasvári Roma neighbourhood -- t7 Linguistic Repertoire: A despised "mixed" language as a resource for learning -- t8 Transformation and translanguaging: Evolving student-teacher roles -- t9 Mediation through translanguaging: The linguistic negotiation of identities and policies -- t10 Teachers' talk in the translanguaging classroom: Monolingual teachers in bi- and multilingual classrooms -- t11 Translanguaging shift and institutional settings: Impact beyond the classroom -- t12 Creating translanguaging space through schoolscape design and reflective practices -- t13 Community-based knowledge in culturally transformative pedagogies -- t14 Translanguaging and written nonstandard language: Heterographic literacy in and outside school -- t15 Adaptive schooling, effective learning organisation, and translanguaging -- t16 Stylisation, voice and crossing in the classroom -- tPart IV: Conclusion -- t17 Conclusion: Participatory ethnography and translanguaging education as forms of transcultural becoming among multilingual Roma in monolingual environments -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThis multi-authored monograph, located in the intersection of translanguaging research and Romani studies, offers a state-of-the-art analysis of the ways in which translanguaging supports bilingual Roma students' learning in monolingual school systems. Complete with a video repository of translanguaging classroom moments, this comprehensive study is based on long-term participatory ethnographic research and a pedagogical implementation project undertaken in Hungary and Slovakia by a group of primary teachers, bilingual Roma participants, and researchers. Co-written by academic and non-academic participants, the book is an essential reading for researchers, pre- and in-service teachers of Romani-speaking students, and experts working with collaborators (learners, informants, activists) whose home languages are excluded from mainstream education and school curricula. The videofiles in the book are available via the following website: http://www.kre.hu/romanitranslanguaging/index.php/video-repository/  aIssued also in print.  afunded by Erasmus+ Strategic Partnership  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: u